Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: Ok, so after seeing all of the comments raving about this film, I watched it.  Wow, what a disappointment.  It's the same plot as the first movie, more or less, with the "twist" that instead of hunting down rogue replicants, our Blade Runner is hunting down the child of a replicant.  The bad guy and the good guys have the same motive, so why are they fighting?  Wallace wants replicants that can procreate.  The rogue replicants want to be able to procreate.  Why are they against one another?  Wallace's replicants are supposed to be perfect now.  No running away.  No disobeying.  So why is there even an army of them ready to start YET ANOTHER rebellion.  The movie ends the same as the first one.  Rebellion of replicants about to take place.  Harrison Ford runs off with his family.  The replicant child isn't even a very viable biproduct.  She's fucking bubble girl.  She can't leave her habitat.  If that's what replicant children will turn out to be, they're 100% useless.  Ain't going to the stars with that.  It's visually stunning, but the plot holes are gigantic and the overall story is pointless.  We've seen this movie before.  This is The Force Awakens of Blade Runner movies.  Just a remake of the first.

Too much explosions and fights, which didn't sit right for me.
And the end, I was so happy that I still gave the sequel a chance, because I really liked it.
Slow paced, yes... but never boring. And they kept the visuals true to the original, without looking outdated.
Also good performance by the actors.
For me personally, this movie is pretty much on par with the original movie.
Which means you probably either love it or loathe it.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
This movie was Brutal, not in a sense that most modern films attempt at portraying, but quite the contrary.
We see society push down on a man who wants to rebel, yet he knows full well he cannot do that without dire consequences.
Though the action is minimal, it makes up for it with a truly tearing story that builds hope, and even drops it right in front of you.

This is a work of art in today's ever worsening Film Industry, as such, it deserves great respect.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
Blade Runner 2049 is brilliant, it's got the same feel as the original & Harrison Ford was icing on the cake, I love all the twists & turns & I love how it all comes together with the original film, The protagonist is very similar to the architect from the matrix.  At first I though it was going to be just another big budget B rated remake like the Total Recall & Judge Dredd remake but it didn't disappoint. The story & the giant blue haired Joi reminded me of Motoko Kusanagi from the ghost in the shell anime & Misato Katsuragi & the giant Rei Ayanami from Neon Genesis Evangelion (the end of Evangelion) https://youtu.be/mfcbhJz8YA0?t=92 
the giant stone head laying on it's side was an obvious nod to the giant head of Rei Ayanami from the end of Evangelion
https://youtu.be/mfcbhJz8YA0?t=218
https://youtu.be/W0ONpH3X6NA?t=259 
So many films have been inspired by the original 1982 blade runner film, I can never get enough of tech-noir cyberpunk films & anime, they always push your mind out of the box.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: This movie is just something else I‚Äôve never seen. Watched it in IMAX and never was the same after. This film transcends all others. To me this is perfection.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: This film just confirmed what I suspected would occur from the moment I heard 2049 was being made...that it's a sequel that shouldn't be made.  Rutger Hauer himself called this film soulless, I couldn't agree more.  It does have its moments,  I will say the cinematography/visuals were intriguing, but at the end of the day this film fails to stand on its own IMHO.  The characters were shallow, the script was disjointed, and the sound was unremarkable.  Unfortunately, this franchise will likely continue with sequels ad nauseum (see Alien); until it just can't be watered down any further...what a shame.

Comment: One thing I dislike about the new Blade Runner is that Wallace's character reminds me too much of Eldon Tyrell. I suppose that he is meant to be an biblical allusion to pharaoh of Egypt and I suppose that Eldon Tyrell is also an biblical allusion to a king of Babylon, as Tyrell lives on top of a ziggurat, a.k.a. tower of Babylon, implying he is trying trying to match up with God.  Wallace's character model also "challenges" God in its own way (the story of Plagues of Egypt). And I feel that this is too much of repetition. I'd be happier if Tyrell's heir was a completly new type of character, similar to Alarich Wallenquist from Sin City; driven solely by greed. It would be a nice change and it would still adhere to neo-noir style.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
A wonderful movie that didn't pander to modern day audiences.  It didn't have the main 3 things that appeal to the average movie goer these days.

Consistent mindless action, attempts at humor around every corner, and one liners.

If you see the top films of 2018, Disney, Star Wars, Marvel, and Dwayne the Rock movies (Jumanji/Rampage etc.) all take the top spots, and they're all the same formula I described above.  It's sad to see a movie where actual effort went into the music, CGI, Story (catering heavily to the original fan base!) are all there, but people hate on it because it requires thought to grasp the story.  Really sad, that if this movie came out in the 80's or 90's before technology ruined everyone's attention span, it would've been appreciated by the modern day movie goer.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: Ryan Gosling's performance was dazzling in this futuristic high-tech dystopia. And while Deckard (Harrison Ford) had been relegated to a secondary yet integral position, it lifted the heart watching him assist with the continuation of the overall Blade Runner story timeline. And is it me, or was Deckard tougher in his old age than back during his Blade Runner days? And while it's incredibly dated, there is a fantastic 'point-and-click' video game from the late 90's that ran parallel to Deckard's investigation. Depending upon the player's choices, and responses from NPCs throughout the game, Ray McCoy's fate was one of a possible sixteen endings. In order to avoid legal issues regarding a complicated copyright, Westwood Studios kept the familiar key locations to a minimum and introduced some background trivia of their own to the Blade Runner universe. They were also allowed to ask cast members to voice their characters from the movie. So there was some degree of connection between the movie and 'its interactive sidequal'. The 'Voight-Kamp' interrogation added some excitement to the gameplay.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
In case of BR2049 an often made complain by the audience feedback was that its story was to complex to understand (which isn¬¥t that complex and even involves a lot of hand holding and pointing fingers). This and its nearly 3 hours runtime which is also too much attention to bear for most nowadays are believed to be some of the major "problems" why this movie didn¬¥t do well. We saw the exact same pattern already several times. As soon a movie needs attention beyond 2 hours people minds start to melt. People also become uncomfortable, which is indeed a cinema house problem I¬¥m myself aware of. I am not super excited for going into cinema but just do it occasionally because my girl loves it. I myself love to watch movies at home and are better able to immerse there. Nowadays with streaming services progressing rapidly, perhaps the cinema exclusivity someday will become past, granting movies more freedom without being tied to a "cinema dogma" dictating cruical things like length. 

However it isn¬¥t the length alone why nowadays complex and intelligent movies often turn out to be dangerous projects. There are many great movie examples that weren¬¥t overly complex but still managed to overtax the crowd or not hit the current "trend-mindset", leading to a dimishing success. Consequence of this is that movie makers and investors may hesitate to progress and better stay true to what they are doing best for too many decades: watered down stories (deus ex machina style) that are just good enough to be carrier vehicles for their actors and their action(s) and cliche movie logic ridden black&white or good&bad characters that enable a simpler mind (if a mind is mandatory at all) to settle down and to easier sort things out. Most nowadays feel already offended when entertainment requires more brain power than barebone sustainment would. 

If you take a look at those mentioned aspects you should see the vicious circle here. Stereotypical movies for a stereotypical crowd that only is able to handle stereotypical - which isn¬¥t just true when it comes to movies. Not that it was better 30 years ago but it certainly didn¬¥t improve

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
I was a little worried about this sequel, not just because Sci-Fi sequels like this are almost impossible to do right, but because the original movie is near and dear to my heart.  Also, there has been quite a bit' of negative press surrounding this movie, most of which I now know is unfounded.

In not so many words, I watched it and....WOW.  I loved it!  Is it as 'good' as the first? I don't think it is possible to approach the vaunted level of the original but I was definitely not disappointed.

To avoid spoilers, I won't go into details but just watch it, especially if you have seen the first movie.

A few stoic Sc-Fi 'critics' and clueless Millennials won't get it but that's ok.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: The film tries to impress us with its connection to the original, when in fact it just cannibalizes the Ridley Scott masterpiece for the only value it has. It's just not organically woven into the new film and it's painfully obvious, right down to the 'imitation Vangelis' soundtrack which is so bad it should be illegal. 2049 has no depth and dimension and points to the work of a very mediocre director re-configuring and dispensing the bland expectations of a 21st century sci-fi audience who are so dumbed-down by 21st century schlock by now that they, sadly, can't tell the difference. I had to keep telling myself that the film had nothing to do with the original just to get through, but then I was left with the stark, 2-dimensionality of a truly poor work that relies on its visual effects and darkest themes to anesthetize the audience into believing they actually saw something worthwhile.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
The story is rather weak, but overall, Blade Runner 2049 is still high art with marvelous production design and more than a few 
emotionally touching scenes included as well.

The first Blade Runner had the same problems (except it didn't have the emotional scenes).
The threadbare story was drowned under the weight of the impressive visuals, and didn't really have an impact at all.

The difference between the original and the sequel is that technology has progressed a lot since 1982, so for modern 
audiences, the visuals are now impressive enough to make up for the lack of a compelling story.
And I'm not saying the original looks bad by today's standards (far from it), but even as I watched it for the first time back in
1985, although I was impressed, it wasn't enough to make me fall in love with the film. It needed something more.

Well, something more is what Blade Runner 2049 offers. It's just a shame that the story still doesn't match the visual
beauty. If it did, we'd be talking about arguably one of the greatest films ever made, instead of "merely" one of the best
sequels of all time. And as it is, I'd actually prefer to watch the film without any of the dialogue.
Just music and some of the sound effects would be more than enough to just sit back, chill, and breathe in the atmosphere.

10/10 for production design.
9/10 for acting.
8/10 for music and sound effects.
6/10 for story.

Overall, a strong 8/10 for the whole thing. Which is MUCH better than the original gets from me.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
So I saw this movie. I freely admit to being an uber fan of the ‚Äúoriginal‚Äù, so much so I become physically ill when I learned of a sequel. Blade Runner, the original, is the greatest movie ever made IMHO. So naturally, I was very very displeased when I saw that Hollywood was going to cash in off the greatness of the original.

This movie, however, stands on its own and Gosling did impress. The underlying story was sublime. Not as profound or well told as the original. But good.

Pros:
Gosling impressed
The underlying story was worthy
Harrison Ford made it happen
Anna de Armas... wow... her character was beautiful in every sense
Absolutely stunningly beautiful movie to behold. Cinematography was breathtaking 

The Bad...
Niander Wallace (Jared Leto) absolutely absurd. Mumbled platitudes,  androids get cut up and shot - presumably fir dramatic effect. An entirely pointless character 
Luv - although not quite as absurd, a confused and over-wrought bad-guy drama that did not come together 

Look, the original was an organic masterpiece. No fake drama or unnecessary platitudes. It was humanity in its very essence. Nothing can compare.

With that in mind, the movie by modern standards is very good. It simply must have the gratuitous nonsensical fight scenes that one must expect from todays action movies, but other that that. 4/5

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: For those of you that find this movie boring, just remember that this is not a mainstream film. It's an artistic film. This is a film that's made with intelligence and for intellectual filmgoers, not the mainstream. The producers were expecting a higher gross profit, as it was distributed by Warner Bros. This may have not been a letdown if _Blade Runner_ is becoming a franchise, but we'll see. The only issue with that is releasing a sequel to a cult classic to a mainstream audience. Now, there are definitely going to be mixed responses. This film is not for everyone, but that doesn't matter. It doesn't have to be a blockbuster to be successful. What matters is that decades from now, people won't be dissecting big buck, repetitive sequels like _Jurassic World_ and _Star Wars VII._ They'll be studying, sharing, and honoring films like _mother!_ and _Blade Runner 2049._

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: I thought this was one of the greatest true science fiction movies I have ever seen.  I will probably see it again this weekend.  For Philip K. Dick fans, this movie  continues with the themes from his novel, "Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep", probably more so than the original "Bladerunner".  I loved it, it was very moving and thought provoking.  I was thrilled that it was much more than just a mindless display of special effects.  The effects were great but not overdone  and everything in this world seems real.  I know it was a long movie but I loved it so much I would have been ok if it were even longer.  I know this will be one of those movies that presents something new every time you see it.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: This film has to be seen at least twice ..... upon 2nd viewing I was more able to isolate and focus on the plight of K and his flirtation, if not seduction, into the plausibility of his humanness without being distracted by other details. His journey was a touching recognition of the possibilities that exist, even within his replicant mind, of living an authentic human life ... he was as crucial a participant as Dekard in this film though his memories were contrived, perhaps like Dekard's, if you believe Rick was also a replicant as Ridley Scott has stated. K (Joe) was a far less vindictive,  more self contained,  gentler version of Rutger Hauer's replicant, capable of compassion yet steadfast in his loyalty to perform as required despite his inferior status.  The splendid soundtrack adds to the viewers cerebral expansion in delving into the depth of such subject matter with grains of urgency, vitality, hope and a burning warmth one might find at a Rave. Oh yes, this film is robust!  Im glad it under performed at the box office like its predecessor. It'll be our little secret. .........but go see it!

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
I watched this a couple of weeks back with my dad - I was the only teenage girl in the cinema hall hahah. It is obvious that the sequel is directed toward men (there is a lot of objectifying of women) - and you can also see that they made a huge effort to make this movie work. First of all, the visuals and the atmosphere are amazing, and grab your attention at once. It's like a modernised, more dramatic and sexier version of the original Blade Runner. The acting, the filming techniques and the way the story is built up - brilliant.

However, I found a couple of scenes - like the romantic ones - a little longer and more accentuated than necessary, though the girl Joi might be in the film to make the audience wonder, what really is the difference between real and fake? Are humans really more genuine than replicants? I think the theme was well chosen, and I appreciate that those who shaped this movie really put in a lot of work. For you can see that every detail was thought through.

There are small moments, details and actions that are copied from the original. Probably to make this one resemble and be connected more to the first film, but for me, it seemed rather unoriginal. I am still unsure whether I like the plotline that sets the foundation for the entire movie - I won't spoil anything, but it is sort of based on a cliche idea that ends up not having much impact on the audience (me) when finally revealed. I was disappointed with how the plot developed, and that there many (albeit little) similarities between the 1982 and 2017 films, that only gave me the impression that they were trying to recreate, or repaint, some of the iconic scenes and traits from the original one. These small semblances seemed just a little superficial and cliche. Or maybe I am being too picky. After all, people always gravitate toward romance in films.
The cinematography - or whatever you call it, visuals and effects - makes up for some of the cheesiness though. But after the first breathless impression, I was left with many questions.
I did read that they planned maybe on making another sequel, and that must be why it ended in a very open way.

Anyway, it is definitely worth watching. You forget the time as you dive deeper into the story - it is beautifully constructed, loads of details that add to the dystopian mood, and it's really intriguing and gives you pieces of information and action at regular intervals, so you never get bored. Do watch Blade Runner 2049! I don't think you'll regret it.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
Scott invented a new type of Movie genre way back in 1982 - Its called INDUSTRIAL SCIENCE FICTION.Since all that time ago he was afraid to continue Bladerunner nevermind announce it being the quiet but very powerful veteran director that he is today.Because of all the harsh criticism and great uncertainty it was recieving back then.It is still considered to be the most powerful cult sci-fi classic of them all.The latest update is 35 years in the making and it's blindlingly powerful.
I honestly thought before I saw it that 164 minutes was too long,but now I reckon its not long enough,the movie completely sucks you in like the industrial hoover that it is and by the time you think that it is too long,it takes you up even faster at supersonic speed by way of the quiet but deadly character K in his flying electric vehicle.It just does not let go of you,You are completely immersed and gripped by its shear power of suspense and by the deadliest and darkest of secrets.It is a1000 times darker than the original and you will love every single second of it,you will not want it to end.The soundtrack keeps you watching,keeps you awake and alert if you are tired and sweeps you away into another world.It shows the difference between what is real and what is fake,what is old and what is new.The old bladerunner model meeting the new model,but that does not mean that new is better and old is just old and useless,far from it.The old always have old tricks that the new doesn't know about,I just love the old dog who keeps Deckard company,who just looks so old and puzzled?I have a thing about black dogs?
There's a poignant moment in the story near the end when a powerful artificial force rams into an even more powerful and relentless natural force that engulfs it and sweeps in and out,which do you think wins?It is the classic AN UNSTOPPABLE FORCE AGAINST AN IMMOVABLE OBJECT.This is a true GIANT OF A SCI-FI MOVIE that is meant for the big screen,it wont be the same watching it on anything smaller.The end of this leaves two wide open doors into a second movie and hopefully a third,a trilogy in the making.Where Rick Deckard finishes what he started all those years ago and leads an Android ( Replicant ) siege war against the humans especially against corporate humans and WINS!Enjoy,enjoy!God bless all,Escapism forever!

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
I went to the movie theater with the open mind, being a fan of the original Blade Runner and sci-fi movies of the 80s in general (Terminator, Alien, Aliens, The Thing, etc.)

I knew it was not going to top the original Blade Runner, but was really excited after watching multiple trailers...

Unfortunately I have to say this is really one of THE WORST sci-fi movies I watched in years. I dont know but the movie is very boring and without character at all. It seems like Hollywood lost its golden spark of the 80s -- the screenplay and character development were so bad I was literally falling asleep... and what about that overhelming sex theme and nudity present throughout?  Are screenwriters of today really feeling this alone is gonna make the movie good??

Overall I am really, really disappointed and going back to my beloved sci-fi flicks from the   80s. NOTHING WILL EVER MATCH THE QUALITY OF THOSE OLD MOVIES.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
When Deckard said Rachael was special, he wasn't kidding. Director Denis Villeneuve does a commendable attempt to pay tribute to the first movie, but that's like trying to make Citizen Kane II. Like the original, it's a visually intense movie, but each scene is not a work of art per the original.

The sound track is heavy and disjointed in spots, and spot on in others. Acting across the board is excellent, even if Gosling still not my first choice, he's solid. If this movie falls short anywhere compared to the original, it's in the dialogue. The original had dialogue I still repeat in my head once in a while, whereas this movie, I can't think of a single scene that will stick in my head. The evil genius in this movie is more a side character, unlike Tyrell, who was one of the most compelling characters in the original. 

The movie both pays pays homage to the original, with some characters and scenes being very reminiscent to the first, and many original to this film. By this review one might think I didn't enjoy 2049, but that's not the case at all. This is a must see movie for fans of the original if for no other reason you get to immerse yourself in all things Blade Runner for almost three hours. I don't think it really added anything to the story per se, but it's one of the better movies I have seen in some time, and any time a thinking person's sci-fi movie is made, must be applauded. This one gets an A.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: Movies are like currency, what it meant in 1982 isn't the same as what it is in 2017. In 1982 Ridley Scott and co. imagined a (retro)future unlike any other and made such a monumental film. Over the years we have become so familiar with androids on film and fiction (Although earlier literature existed), that the original Blade Runner will not impress newer film-goers much and convert them. But as a product of its time, everything about the movie was innovative and still holds up very well, down to the effects and score. In comparison a 2017 release of a sequel doesn't have to tackle much in terms of a visual style or substance since they have already been well established. I feel in that sense, we haven't really imagined real sci-fi in years. I enjoyed 2049 since it didn't destroy what the original was or dumb it down with mere action. But I still feel the original had a momentum alongside its philosophy that the new one replaces with stares, silences and pauses. It could have been shorter and more potent.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
I actually saw this movie, and I didn't like it. *WARNING TO EVERYONE WHO WANTS TO WATCH THE MOVIE, DO NOT CONTINUE TO READ WHAT I HAVE TO TYPE!*

The entire movie was slow-paced. It was almost 3 hours, which I cannot watch an movie that is so close to that time period. I can watch Forest Gump and Star Wars (since these movies are also 2-3 hours at least). But this movie literally was half of a waste of time. Like there are parts I cannot understand why they need to include in this. *UH I HOPE PEOPLE WHO HATE SPOILERS ARE GONE!* There is this part where this harlot and the main character were going to have sex, and the scene went by so slow, that in the other half of the film it seemed like that happened in another movie. It was so slow that it should have been a two part movie. It was a good movie with a great plot, but I did not like how it was all put into plan. I fell asleep a couple parts of it, to be honest. My dad and I ordered a large popcorn and it was a big container. About 40ish minutes in the movie it was gone. We don't chug down popcorn in movies either (just to let you know that incase you think the reason why the popcorn didn't last long because we choked ourselves with the popcorn xD). But yeah, if you do not like sitting in uncomfortable movie theater chairs (if your near theater didn't upgrade the seats) for 3 hours, then I don't recommend watching this. If you want to watch this when it comes out in dvd, have at it. BTW when I saw this, the theater had the surround sound so loud my entire body was shaking. Even my dad, who listens to Metallica on full blast, even complained how loud it was.

Comment:
I absolutely fucking loved this movie. 
The sound design and visuals were orgasmic
The story was eh, but it held my attention pretty well. 
There were some boring parts, but not many at all and they were quickly set aside by something else. 
Probably my favorite thing about this whole movie, though, was the music. It's like the movie was made for the soundtrack and not the other way around. The music told the story just as well, if not even better than the dialogue and characters did. You KNEW you were in the city because of this sound, you KNEW you were somewhere special because of the other sound, etc etc. Hans Zimmer did a fan fucking tastic job as usual, and I was not at all surprised when I learned that he wrote the music score

I think the reason people are defending this movie so viciously is because they can easily do it with the backing of the critics. It's apparent that this will be obtain a cult following like the first - but to say that it will be a cult classic? This movie will be quickly forgotten once the hype fades.

Comment:
Blade Runner 2049:  boring snoozefest, CG overload swill, obnoxious score, bad dialogue, minimal tension, and a miscast Leto.  The production design of Gosling's "Drive" apartment was more "Blade Runner" than his 2049 generic Alcatraz cell, or Robin Wright's Soviet era LAPD office (I know, for effect, but still flat).  Harrison Ford and Olmos were great to see, wanted Sean Young, Daryl Hannah, or M. Emmet Walsh in it, but w/ a good script, though.  
Blade Runner, 1982 = groundbreakingly HFS.  
Blade Runner 2049 = heartbreakingly DOA.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: This movie had big shoes to fill and man does it fill them. Blade runner 2049 is fascinating, brilliant , intelligent , insightful, gripping and smart piece of filmmaking. You can clearly observe and see how this is a work of an artist who respects the craft and with each movie tries to make a name for himself. This movie works on so many levels starring from stellar performances , great script , interesting and fleshed out characters , intriguing story which by the way plays out as detective investigation for the most of the film, mind-blowing direction and cinematography combined with excellent production values and eerie compositions. I also enjoyed  reversed psychological approach this movie makes with making its protagonist replicant in search for his possible human heritage while the original had human doubting if he is replicant. Great thing about it and not everyone can achieve that is how you get reasoning behind every character no matter if they are good or bad and you understand their actions so they don't end up being generic cartoon characters like in some sci fi films.  2049 is everything modern sci fi needs, it has its own identity and for my money it gets perfect 5 out of 5.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
I was excited to see the new Blade Runner, because like many, the first is one of my cult movies ... The images are formidable footprints of lyricism, morbid fairy tales, very contemporary. The shots are amazingly stunning surprising with colors whose tones are reversed the warm colors are icy and vice versa. but depressed at wish, with a Ryan Gosling, marble, a Harrisson Ford that appears much too late in the film, and a deafening music that terrorizes ... It is a dystopia that could have been very successful because Villeuneuve addresses the dear themes to humanity, who is it? What is man's own? Is it to have memories? Is it the fact of having a soul? Can it happen again? it is approached sometimes in a subtle way sometimes not ... The film is too long, too contemplative, without real scenes of actions and when they exist they too are too long without punch. Of course, we have the right to a love scene mi real mi virtual , where one wonders where reality begins, hence the questions of memories, real or implanted memories? Villeuneuve sees the future with spleen and melancholy, it is certainly a choice and if the first opus of Blade Runner could look sad, there was a kind of underlying hope ... Here it is mortifer ..
I advise the film for those who like me adore the images, a frantic aesthetic unparalleled, I advise against the film, for those like me adore the SF and blockbusters SF, the contemplative is good but 2:40 is too much!

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
For anyone considering watching this movie, I'd highly recommend that you do not. Being genuine, it was the most boring piece of well funded shit I've ever seen in my entire life. It only begins to get good in the last quarter and even then it's just not very entertaining.

I had seen this with my family and I thought it was just me who found it underwhelming; turns out they were pretty disappointed too.

I acknowledge that like 99% percent of people in the comments are saying stuff like "omg! This is the best movie I've ever seen" and that they think that it's amazing and what not, but this is just my honest opinion: It seriously lacks in action, it's over complicated (at least for people who hadn't seen the first movie) and it's waaay to slow paced.

This is a movie for those who enjoy it's lore, but if you don't understand it/don't give a shit about the over complicated lore, then you'll be sat bored af in the cinema for two and a half hours.

Don't get triggered at me, it's just a disclaimer for anyone considering watching this that your time and money could be better spent (cough cough Kingsman cough cough the Golden Circle) errrhem.

Comment: Ana Da Armas makes the movie. It's not quite as good as reviews make out. It might only be an 8/10. I mean, it has some very obvious fan service introduced indecently early (in a unlikely scene given the adversary). But it doesn't have the totally neo-noir feel throughout of the original,  or the spellbinding lines, or the showing of industrial imagery always with a decaying mystery to them, rather than a cathedral-like awe of them. It could have used Ridley Scott's touch in some of the places where it looks just like any sci-fi film. The question of what is a real relationship, the depressing idea of could an artificial relationship be the most moving one that someone have, is the most interesting in the movie and that largely happens when Ana Da Armas is on screen in her various scenes.

Comment:
Interestingly enough Jared Leto's character is wrong, most civilizations were built not with slaves, but paid workers. Sure there was slave labor, but many of the major cities we know of today started off as forts, built so the people who lived nearby could go there if they were in danger. For example, many of the Celtic/Gaulic peoples (Gauls were Celts, not all Celts were Gauls) utilized indentured servants. This was a common system all over the world, until Caesar committed genocide against the Gauls...the Romans decided slaves were property. Now that doesn't mean Roman slaves were never freed, many slaves became powerful and wealthy during and after their freedom.¬†

Now yes, the Russian serfs were slaves, but they didn't really build civilization, mainly they farmed for a wealthy noble. What really changed Russia was Peter the Great, with his love for western style sailing, and really everything Western Europe...which he then forced westernization on Russia..

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
IT'S GONNA BE A FLOP. THE BIGGEST SCOTT'S MISTAKE WAS TO CONSIDER AN EXPENSIVE ATTEMPT OF P. C. DICK'S NOVEL "DO ANDROIDS DREAM OF ELECTRIC SHEEP" ADAPTATION COULD BE A POSSIBLE COMMERCIAL SUCCESS. VILENEUVE'S CRITICAL ACCLAIM IS MUCH GREATER, THAN HIS REAL ABILITIES. THE CAST OF THE SEQUEL SEEMS TO BE A MISTAKE, IT'S EXAGGERATED LENGTH IS APPARENTLY DUBIOUS . I THINK, WE ARE ABOUT TO SEE THE "DISSAPOINTMENT OF THE YEAR". THE MOVIE SHALL NEVER BREAK EVEN, ALTHOUGH IT IS GONNA MAKE THE "PRODUCTION BUDGET", AS GOOD, AS THE 1982 MOVIE, BUT IT WILL NEVER BE THE SAME CRITICAL SUCCESS.
HAVING SEEN THE MOVIE I SHOULD SAY, THAT IT IS FULL OF VISUAL EFFECTS AND PROMISING PREMISES, BUT IT'S NEVER-ENDING PLOT, TOO SIMILAR TO THE "STAR WARS: THE FORCE AWAKENS'"(AND SIMPLIER, BUT FULL OF RUDE, REPULSIVE VIOLENCE), IS A MESS. I WOULD CALL THIS MOVIE TEDIOUS AND SOGGY. PROBABLY, THE REBOOT, WITH A PLOT, FAR CLOSER TO THE DICK'S ORIGINAL NOVEL(BUT CHEAPER, MADE FOR A MODEST COST AROUND 50-60 MILLION), COULD BE EVEN MORE INTERESTING.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
Blade Runner already gave us the point it was trying to make, it already presented its ideas, ideas of what it means to be human, ideas of nihilism, identity. And thats why this movie is considered a masterpiece, and having a sequel without any depth, without its own statement, without any new ideas that blade runner hasn't already made, would make that sequel not only bad, but also an insult to the intellectual heritage that this work of art truly is. 
And people talking that the sequel looks promising without having any insight of what the story is about, but by simply looking at the scenes and actors show how ignorant and shallow their 'critical opinion' is, how they dont have a single clue what makes a movie great, what made blade runner great. Disgustng.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: When I first saw this trailer in theaters, I didn't quite get what was happening like a lot of people. I loved the music, the futuristic sci-fi colors and atmosphere, and the actors. I saw Denis' name came up as director and Ridley Scott as exec producer, and I was instantly excited because I knew that from these 2 guys' amazing works in the past, this will automatically be amazing. Yet all I knew about blade runner was that Ridley Scott made the original with Harrison in the 80s, and it had gotten some of the best reviews I've ever seen, from both critics and fans. Last night I saw the original's final cut remastered, went back to this trailer, and NOW I'm officially excited. If you're new to Blade Runner, what hypes this movie up for fans is the theme music, the part where Ryan gosling wants to ask Harrison some questions, and the shiny eyes of some characters that Jared Leto has. If you haven't seen the original Blade Runner, DEFINITELY see it! You'll get what's going on right away, and you'll be just as hyped. Great cast and team putting this together also. Can't wait.

Just look at it - It's got all the hallmarks of cheap imitation, meant as a commercial cash grab. Full of fake CGI and shallow characters. Too fast, too overwhelming, too forced, too many explosions, not enough love or personality to it.

Blade Runner was an Original that cannot be replicated (intended) - A saudade meditation and study in cyberpunk atmosphere lovingly crafted through deliberate slow pacing, careful visual design (Syd Meade), pain-staking perspective shots, old-school special effects, and analog synth-wave meant to mimic orchestral movements, done by a master (Vangelis). It created a sense of beautiful loneliness, isolation, and melancholy, of a living breathing futuristic city. You could smell the rain and neon in every scene. It created an emotional depth greater than the sum of its production parts.

Moreover, the actors were participants who spoke little, and their dialogue left space to breathe in between sentences, allowing the viewer to soak up each scene. The underlying theme was they were dealing with an existential crisis that was bigger than themselves - there was no-one to blame, no real enemy - almost a tragedy of sorts. And yet they could
 have been anyone on the street - you or me. 

I'll leave you with this - to "get" what Blade Runner is all about, what I'm talking about here - One only needs listen to Vangelis' Blade Runner Blues, while keeping the spectacular visuals in mind. It is truly one of a kind Sci-Fi Noir movie that was inspired by the culture and technology of decade it lived in (1980s), and its vision of the future still echoes with us today. I highly doubt this sequel can live up to it, and nor should it - You don't mess with a classic.

Comment:
Action?

Why?

The first Blade Runner was awesome precisely because it was a dark, moody, noir trip _that did NOT appeal to the lowest common denominator <cough>Siskel&Ebert<cough>._

In fact, everything that made the original so incredible,  caused it to BOMB at the theaters and it was only kept alive by people like me (yes, the hard core OG fanbois) wearing out our Beta copies with repeated viewings until the masses caught on 10-15 years after it's release.

They've basically turned the tale into a formulaic action movie cash grab that appears to look and flow no different than "Elysium" or the "Total Recall" and "Judge Dredd" remakes.

<sigh>

Yeah, I'll definitely check it out on Kodi (eventually), but if these trailers are any indication, there's NO WAY "2049" will be even REMOTELY on par with the original.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
If Harrison Ford wasn't in this movie then I think I'd be more excited for it than I am. Not that I don't rate him as an actor, I really do, but it ruins the entire point of the original Blade Runner. The whole point of that movie was to examine the meaning of being human and humanity itself through the use of existentialism, and letting the viewer determine what and who Deckard actually  is. 

Casting him in a Blade Runner movie 30 years after the original was set ruins the ambiguity of the whole movie and kind of diminishes the point of it, because it sort of confirms he isn't a replicant, despite the original strongly hinting that he was a replicant. Even Ridley Scott claimed he was. Yes, the book was written with Deckard as a human, but the movie, like Fight Club, is its own piece of media, and is so highly acclaimed because of the themes it explores. 

Unless the movie comes up with a really clever, and I mean really clever, way of explaining things to do with Deckard, then it will sort of ruin the legacy of the original.
With this in mind, the cinematography looks fantastic and the casting choice also looks really promising. I like the kind of neo-noir feel to it that the original also had, so in that respect it does look good, it's just how they handle the story and characters that makes me slightly apprehensive.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
"Every civilization was built off the back of a disposable workforce. But I can only make so many..." -- Neander Wallace (Jared Leto)

Here it sounds like Mr. Wallace, who is a replicant manufacturer, can't keep up with demand. Replicants only have a four-year lifespan, so the pressure to manufacture a great number of them must be immense. It's too much. Hence his statement that he "can only make so many."

At 1:32 we hear about something being "finally unearthed." Wallace then sends a female operative to "bring it to me" -- presumably the secret that has been unearthed. Is it possible that what Wallace is hunting for is the secret to creating replicants with longer lifespans?

If that is true, then perhaps Deckard is a replicant after all -- but one of the "special" replicants who have lifespans longer than just four years. And perhaps Officer K (Ryan Gosling) is the same as Deckard. Indeed, we are told that he too is "special"...

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
Looks as if they totally sensationalized and flanderized what was in the original movie and book. "There is an order to things... that's what we do here..." the writing and acting sounds so over-dramatized - I just don't like it. Assuming she's a law enforcement character (could be wrong), compare her dialogue and tone with Byrant's when he brings Deckard in; Byrant sounds natural, like a guy who works a job, has bills to pay, and isn't really thinking of all this high idea stuff but is just trying to get his job done (it's even better in the book). This is a complaint I have about more than just this new BR but more less about new movies in general. Everything is so big in scale, over-dramatized, and ultimately dumbed down. "The key to the future..." What? In the book the androids and technological advances aren't being made for such lofty ideas; they're being produced for more realistic purposes like making a profit or bringing pleasure. It's just like what happened with both Jurassic World and the new Star Trek films.

And yes I realize that this could just be the trailer, but I'm not going to get my hopes up. I'm honestly not a big fan of the original film, but I do respect it on a number levels. This new film looks like a - slightly drier than most - new movie with Blade Runner's skin. Honestly if you want to get the best experience with this world than read the novel by Philip K. Dick. I'm reading it right now, and I absolutely love it. Existential questions, what religions can be brought about by technology, nihilism and other cool themes, jobs in the new world, way more exploration of the world and action than in the original film (even the original film doesn't compare IMO).

Composer: J√≥hann J√≥hannsson (Prisoners, I Am Here, The Theory of Everything, Arrival) and Hans Zimmer (The Lion King, Pirates of the Caribbean, The Dark Knight, Inception, 12 Years a Slave, Interstellar, Batman vs. Superman, Dunkirk)

The cast and crew are EXTREMELY impressive, and continue to fuel my hope for this sequel. I'm hoping Blade Runner 2049 pulls a Mad Max Fury Road: an action film that takes everyone by surprise, due to its masterful composition -- cinematography, score, editing, (practical) stunts, acting, etc.

At the end of the first Blade runner, we all wondered how long Rachel would last and whether Deckard was a replicant.  Sean Young went nuts so rachel isn't in this one, and Deckard is now played by a guy who is 70.  Are there questions?  Are there answers?  Does anyone really care?  Hollywood just want to make money and theaters just want you to stuff your face with corn.  CGI, lame dialogues, explosions, and no plot at all.
Don't expect there to be any amazing memes or underlying philosophy.  That went out a long time ago.  This rehash is a cheap ripoff, where the producers don't even care about the material, and fanboys waste their time trying to hold onto their childhood in a cheap ripoff and reboot studio system that dumbs down everything for a foreign audience that didn't understand what the first movie was even about, cause that was American.  This generic dumbed down crap has all the visuals and some of the really old actors, but it is just a cheap ripoff to make money on nostalgia and vague enough for people who didn't understand the culture behind the first movie to not be confused.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
At this time, there are 11,705,892 views, and it's been out only a few days.  That tells me that there is some enthusiasm for this.  That pleased me, as it looks like a very fine sequel.  it seems to have lots of moving parts and what they've done with the music gave me goosebumps.  I hope they'll be using that theme.  

A key point of the trailer that sticks out for me, that ratchets the conflict, is when Gosling says, with that steely glare, "I want to ask you some questions."  Oh, man.  It looks like the mystery will be answered with some finality.  I really can't get a fix on the plot, what's turning the screws, but I don't think I need to know more.  

The cinematography is gorgeous, of course.  Thank you, Roger Deakins.

Comment: Arrival was awful, yet everyone claimed that they liked it. And then a month later, I would talk to people. They would ask me "what did you think of Arrival" and i'll tell them that I hated it, and they'll be like "wait same, why did everyone say that they liked it?!" I think it has to do with the reviews. Arrival is the most perfectly reviewable movie; so fucking bland that reviewers couldn't find any fault with it. The perfectly recommendable film; no personality, nothing to rub anyone the wrong way. The Aliens were hands, the spaceship was a textureless smooth object, the two main love interests had absolutely no chemistry, the animation was glaringly bad (like it was daring you to criticize it), doesn't even follow the original short story. And great, that same director is doing Bladerunner Fuck. It looks like Bladerunner + Mad Max + Dues Ex. Jared Leto as Tyrel? LOL. It looks like they replicated all the sets from the original, just CG as fuck, and lacking any sort of world building probs so it can look like a drake music video. I hope this bombs like Ghost in the Shell and Oblivion, so that Villeneuve doesn't get to direct Dune.

Plot

Spoiler warning:¬†Plot or ending details follow.

Shortly after his activation,¬†David 8¬†is interviewed by Sir¬†Peter Weyland¬†in a palatial lakeside apartment, and David expresses his confusion at having to serve humans, despite being immortal and, in his eyes, superior. Many years later, the colony spaceship¬†USCSS¬†Covenant¬†is en route to the planet Origae-6, carrying over 2,000 colonists in¬†hypersleep. Still more than seven years from its destination, the vessel is struck by the shockwave from a nearby stellar ignition, causing major damage and starting several fires on board. In response to the crisis, the ship's crew are awoken from hypersleep, although Captain¬†Branson¬†is incinerated inside his cryotube when it fails to open. The surviving crew manage to bring the disaster under control, although 47 colonists are lost alongside their captain.

The¬†Covenant's first officer, the highly religious¬†Chris Oram, assumes command of the mission. While undertaking a spacewalk to conduct exterior repairs, pilot¬†Tennessee¬†picks up a fragmented, distorted transmission via his suit's communications systems. When the message is analyzed on board, the crew are able to discern an unidentified human humming a classic rock song within the image. When they trace the transmission to its source, they find it originated from a nearby planet perfect for human habitation, better even than the predictions for Origae-6. Presented with a seemingly perfect home just a few weeks away and with none of the crew wanting to re-enter hypersleep after witnessing Branson's fate, Oram elects to investigate. Branson's wife¬†Daniels¬†officially protests but is overruled.

Upon reaching the uncharted world, Tennessee,¬†Ricks¬†and¬†Upworth¬†remain aboard the¬†Covenant¬†in orbit while the rest of the crew heads to the surface in a dropship to explore. They discover a verdant world ripe in vegetation but mysteriously devoid of animal life. As they explore, one of the security team,¬†Ledward, disturbs some small pods, causing several airborne particles to enter his ear unnoticed. Further searching leads the ground team to a crashed¬†EngineerJuggernaut, inside which they find a¬†dog tag¬†belonging to a "Dr.¬†E. Shaw", as well as the source of the transmission they received. The expedition is cut short when Ledward becomes rapidly and violently ill.¬†Karine¬†rushes him back to the dropship, whereupon a¬†Neomorph¬†erupts from his back before attacking and killing Karine. In a desperate attempt to kill the creature, dropship pilot¬†Faris¬†accidentally shoots several flammable tanks aboard the ship, causing an explosion that kills her and destroys the craft; the Neomorph escapes. Outside,¬†Hallett¬†is killed birthing a second Neomorph from his mouth, having also been infected by the pods.

The Neomorphs, already grown larger, soon return to attack the crew on the ground. The armed security team manage to kill one of the creatures, while the second is scared away by a mysterious hooded figure. Unable to contact the¬†Covenant¬†due to ionic interference and with the ship unable to breach the planet's powerful atmospheric storms anyway, the crew follow the mysterious figure. He leads them to a nearby ruined city, strewn with the bodies of dead Engineers. Upon reaching a vast temple at its center, the figure reveals himself to be David, survivor of the¬†USCSS¬†Prometheus. He explains that he and Shaw came to the planet ten years previously aboard the Juggernaut; however, the ship's cargo of weaponized¬†black liquid¬†accidentally deployed over the city when they arrived, annihilating its populace and contaminating the planet. The Juggernaut then crashed, killing Shaw and leaving David alone.

David and the¬†Covenant's own¬†android,¬†Walter, a later version of the same model, spend time bonding in the temple. However, David soon becomes disappointed in his successor's lack of capacity for emotion and higher thought ‚Äî aspects of his own design deemed dangerous and subsequently removed ‚Äî and kills him. Meanwhile, the surviving Neomorph, now fully-grown, infiltrates the temple and kills¬†Rosenthal. David discovers the creature feeding on her corpse and seems to communicate peacefully with it, but Oram bursts in and shoots the Neomorph dead, enraging David. When Oram threatens him, demanding to know the truth about his actions on the planet, David leads him to a laboratory, where he presents his efforts to genetically engineer a superior lifeform from the creatures spawned by the black liquid. He leads Oram onward into a chamber in the lower levels of the temple, where several¬†Eggs¬†of his creation reside. One of the Eggs promptly opens and Oram is subdued by the¬†Facehugger¬†that emerges.

David waits and watches as Oram is later killed by the¬†Chestburster¬†it lays within him. When the remaining security officers go to investigate, Sergeant¬†Lope¬†is also attacked by a Facehugger, although he is saved when¬†Ankor¬†cuts it off of him, badly burning Lope's face in the process. Ankor is then killed by the fully grown Alien while Lope flees. Elsewhere in the temple, Daniels confronts David, correctly guessing that Shaw did not perish in the crash. David confirms that he killed Shaw during his experiments before attacking Daniels. She is saved by Walter, who, as a more advanced synthetic than David, is able to self-repair. The two androids engage in a brutal duel as Daniels flees. She and Lope manage to contact the¬†Covenant¬†and Tennessee launches a rescue in the ship's cargo transporter sled. Daniels, Lope and Walter make it aboard the small ship, although they are pursued by the Alien. Daniels battles the creature aboard the flying craft, finally crushing it in the vessel's remote crane.

Upon returning to the¬†Covenant, the survivors prepare to re-enter hypersleep. However, Daniels and Tennessee discover Lope has been killed by a Chestburster. The Alien quickly slaughters Ricks and Upworth as they shower, but Daniels and Tennessee manage to corner the creature in the ship's terraforming equipment bay, finally succeeding in ejecting it into space. As they return to hypersleep, Daniels realises too late that it is not Walter who is aboard the ship with her ‚Äî it is David. She cries out in vain as he activates her hypersleep pod. Now alone aboard the vessel, David enters the hypersleep bay full of colonists, looking upon the hundreds of bodies in stasis, before regurgitating several small Facehugger embryos and placing them into storage.

And this trailer kinda does the same thing, they're sorta making it out to be this action film, which is dumb cause I'd rather make a trailer that fits the movie, even if it doesn't appeal to the general audiences. That way it attracts the people who actually want to see the movie instead of tricking people who came to see explosions but I guess that wouldn't make them enough money. Well here's to hoping the film is anywhere as good as the original, I'm still gonna see it regardless so I can say when I was your age I got to see a Blade Runner film in theaters to my kids in 2049!

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: while certainly looking like a nice bowl of eye candy, I fear that a lot of the things that made Blade runner great will be lost in translation with the sequel/reboot? Like the philosophical questions about what does it mean to be human? is it your memories that make you a person? Is it your compassion towards animals/living creatures? (test administered to Leon to see if he is a replicant) the postmodern elements, bricolage of noir (detective, femme fatale,) sci fi(self-explanatory.) aztec tokyo la architecture etc. It had the visual effects but they were extremely credible thanks to the use of the practical physical stuff that we see the actors interacting with (the cars that leave steam when they fly off,  the market scene which is incredible world building) not to mention the amazing performances of Harrison Ford, Rutger Hauer, Sean Young, Daryl Hannah, etc. Frankly Gosling and Jared Leto don't do shit for me. Maybe i'm wrong and it'll be the next masterpiece of our time and hopefully it won't go down like the ghost in the shell reboot.

Comment: I read the novel before I saw Blade Runner way back when and although the movie was incredible I remember leaving the cinema thinking, 'the book was better'. The novel presents a shabby, diseased world suffering the effects of a kind of low-exchange nuclear war where so many humans are now genetically damaged and most animals are extinct. Not some dark, gleaming megalopolis. In the novel the replicants are androids. Soulless versions of living creatures. Their superiority is physical and mental but not spiritual. The central premise of the novel is that living things have, to various degrees, empathy. And that living things need other living things around them to excite empathy and to keep the desire to live going. The replicants are attempting to replace humans and might succeed. But humans have been drawn to a new religion called Mercerism that involves entering an empathetic vision world with the help of an electronic device. Something no replicant can participate in. It was all so much more subtle and tragic than the movie. And this trailer shows the unfortunately lifeless effect that CGI can produce and from what I can see, presents a vision of a dystopia not much different than any one of the others in movies made  in the last 15 years.  And if it is about Harrison Ford having a half-human, half-replicant son, well, thanks, I already saw 'The Force Awakens'.

Comment: I'm not sure about casting Harrison Ford. It feels like it's probably a choice just to help give this movie some cred with fans and add another big name to draw people to the box office and it feels like it was probably a compromise by the writers that won't actually add much to the movie. I mean I don't have much to go on to be fair, but a movie like this should be fairly straight faced sci-fi. It shouldn't be over the top where it doesn't need to be and with that said what are the chances that a in character who in the grand scheme of things isn't important within this movie's world would factor into an amazing story twice. Maybe Gosling is a replicant of the same design and that's why, but if I can guess that from a trailer then that's poor writing in itself.

Comment:
Blade Runner 2049 will be the Force Awakens of the Blade Runner series. It's a "sequel", but it's actually a remake in which the first movie's story happens beat for beat. Again. It will be far too self-aware of its predecessor's success and will endlessly reference things from the first one to the point it will become nauseating. Ryan Gosling will be Deckard and Rachael's son somehow, being the first human/replicant hybrid. That's why he's so "special." His birthday is October 6, 2021. That's why they're using "birthday" in place of "incept date" now.

I'd bet money on this if I weren't poor.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: Rather impressed with the trailer.  Cinematography is top notch, Gosling brings along his delectable noire persona, Joi is beguiling and deceptively innocent while Ford resurrects the cut and dry Deckard of lore (an early model with rudimentary emotional buffers).  Leto is trying too hard as usual and channels the Joker in his Happy Birthday comment (tone it down about 70%) while Leto's assistant appears wooden, from her inelegant walk cycles to her pretend stare.  The new Spinner is a clumsy design compared to the original and reminds one more of a failed electric car startup.  I do like that they at least threw in an ode to a Syd Mead conveyance at 1:52.  They also resurrected the original farm scene with Bautista (good casting) - I personally liked the off world intro better.  As an aside, it would have been a much more interesting dynamic if Bautista played Leto's role.  Surprised Ridley is involved with Yorkin again considering Yorkin never did understand nor admire or respect the original.  Overjoyed that Fancher finally gets his much deserved turn at the helm.  Ridley's crude handling of Alien Covenant left me a bit in shock but his selection of Villeneuve seems to be on point.  So far so good.

Comment:
I really appreciate the work that went into this. From the musical choice, to the set juxtaposition shifting with the dialogue. The whole thing has really solid theme at it's core. And that theme of coarse is minimizing Jared Leto's role in the film. From the visual of a limp lifeless body spilling onto the ground during Leto's first voice over to give us a nice visual of his dead pan acting. Then the studios all flash their logos as if ashamed to be associated. 

The next time Leto damns this movie with his voice over we are treated to shot of some dirt being brushed aside, which can only be a metaphor for where they found the script. Finally punctuating Leto's horrid voice over with two loud pistol shots probably an Easter egg to the two writers Hampton Fancher and Michael Green committing suicide after turning in the script.

Keep up the abysmal work cause China will just bail you out.

Comment:
Gosling! Why did it have to be Gosling? 
Sorry I'm not a fan, He is as believable as a block of cheese, with two goggly eyes that are disturbingly close together. Ok that was harsh..
The film looks beautiful..
I just feel he was miscast for this film, (and most of his roles of late)

I know my dislike of his acting, is kind of irrational.. 
Hummm? Why? I think it literally is the placement of his eyes, they are close together, and his eyebrows (he needs to stop over trimming them) And his little up turned mouth, always Looks like he has a perpetual smirk. even when he is supposed to be sad, or mad. He looks like a little kid that's up to no good.. It's weird how it bothers me. 

Yet He seems Like a nice guy out in the real world.
When I saw "La La Land" I wanted to love the movie, I wanted to like him, But I could not believe in his performance, I could not relate, even though there was a lot in that film for me to relate to. In the end I felt the film was over rated, very pretty with some nice songs, and heart, but .. But not best picture worthy ..

He just looks Meh in this, I really don't buy him as a Bladerunner.. But maybe I will be surprised but I doubt it..

But this is a Beautiful Looking Movie, and I will go to see it.. At least once ...

Comment:
They say not to judge the book by the cover, but....
Harrison Ford had grit to pull off Deckard in the original. Gosling looks childish to the point of being comical. Seriously, I could not stop laughing because of the hysteria ensued for I naively expected a masterpiece. On introspection, what I actually want is Blade Runner 2, with all the same actors, scenery, score and execution. This is not happening and hence my mind is refusing to accept this fact. My, my....Also, the other guy, Leto, "I can only make so much" with eyes of an owl, just looks like a hipster psycopath, no finesse in his execution as Joel Turkel brought back in the day to play Eldon Tyrell.

Remember, the original set an unreachable benchmark:story, cast, visuals, designs, pace, execution, score. This is already lacking in the actor department. Oh well. Feels bad man.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: Rather impressed with the trailer.  Cinematography is top notch, Gosling brings along his delectable noire persona, Joi is beguiling and deceptively innocent while Ford resurrects the cut and dry Deckard of lore (an early model with rudimentary emotional buffers).  Leto is trying too hard as usual and channels the Joker in his Happy Birthday comment (tone it down about 70%) while Leto's assistant appears wooden, from her inelegant walk cycles to her pretend stare.  The new Spinner is a clumsy design compared to the original and reminds one more of a failed electric car startup.  I do like that they at least threw in an ode to a Syd Mead conveyance at 1:52.  They also resurrected the original farm scene with Bautista (good casting) - I personally liked the off world intro better.  As an aside, it would have been a much more interesting dynamic if Bautista played Leto's role.  Surprised Ridley is involved with Yorkin again considering Yorkin never did understand nor admire or respect the original.  Overjoyed that Fancher finally gets his much deserved turn at the helm.  Ridley's crude handling of Alien Covenant left me a bit in shock but his selection of Villeneuve seems to be on point.  So far so good.

Comment: Man, why can't they just leave well enough alone... Blade Runner was already a cult classic, and it was mysterious and really fit the cyberpunk motif... I'm pretty sure the reason they do this is to attract people that want nostalgia, and make money safely... They know it's easier to get ticket sales when it has Blade Runner in the title, but that's scummy I wish Hollywood would just try and make NEW stories, and not live off of sequels... Blade Runner was good, it didn't need a sequel it told it's story... Sigh... Star Wars, Blade Runner, Ghost in the Shell, Alien already were classics and didn't need more movies just leave it alone stop trying to milk every series till the become hollow shells. Make new stories please....

Here is my prediction on the story since they revealed so much in this trailer.

Gosling finds out/discovers that he is a Replicant. We find out that the Blade Runner's were always Replicants. He searches out Rick Deckerd because he was a Replicant that somehow figured out how not to die.

Why do I believe that? In 2007's making of the Final Cut Documentary for the 25th anniversary release, Ridley Scott said "Deckerd IS a Replicant". I highly doubt he would allow the writers to change that fact in his mind.

So Deckerd has survived after all these years and Gosling needs to figure out how "to survive".

There is your movie Blade Runner 2049.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: Five seconds into this trailer, it's already the antithesis of the sombre, understated intelligence of everything that made the original so special. I really don't want to hate on this without giving it a chance, but this sequel looks like every trailer for every wham-bam, watch-and-forget franchise of recent times. I know everybody is very excited (as they are when they see every new Transformers, Superhero and alien invasion movie trailers). Nothing changes. Movies like this aren't made to be good - they're made to be passable while raking in millions of dollars. They count on (and rightly so) the short memories of people (weren't you all jumping up and down at the last Superman trailer?) and they do well, and Hollywood bangs out more and more and more. I'm sure this will look aesthetically blockbusterish and loads of people will see it and then X-Men 12 will bring out a new trailer a month later and we'll all forget this one and jump up and down and it will begin all over again. It's a shame that they can't just let beautiful things rest gracefully in peace.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: *Okay guys, just here me out.* What if this sequel is as *amazing* as the original but in a completely different way. Ever heard of sequels like *Aliens, Terminator: Judgment Day, Empire Strikes Back, Superman II, Mad Max: Road Warrior, Friday The 13th Pt. 2, Evil Dead 2, Indiana Jones: Temple Of Doom, Sam Raimi's Spider-Man 2, and The Dark Knight.* What do *ALL* these sequels have in common? They're more action packed than their originals and have a whole different tone in the films. Some fans would even say these films are better than the first. I'm not saying 2049 will be better but who knows yet for sure? Yes, I highly doubt that. Still, this film *DOES* have a *HUGE* potential to being just as damn near perfect as Scott's Blade Runner. That's all I'm saying. From what I've seen so far, it his all the same formulas as the sequels I've listed.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
I hope they stick with the film noir style of the first. The foundation of the original Blade Runner was, first and foremost, a noir detective story. It was all about a cop tracking down and "retiring" replicants. 

The cyberpunk aesthetic and the "what does it mean to be human" message that came from it were a result of the writer and director's vision for this detective story (Ridley Scott said it himself that he was so inspired by the noir films of the 40s and 50s that he wanted Ford's character to also wear a fedora along with the trenchcoat, but ultimately decided against it since it would end up looking too similar to another one of Ford's projects during that time: Indian Jones). 

I believe that in order for this film to be great, it needs to remember that the story has old film noir, detective story roots. If it focuses too much on the extras (like aesthetics for example) then I fear it will not capture the essence of the original, and what made it great. If that occurs, then this movie will just end up in the "not-as-good-as-the-original" pile, and will quickly be forgotten. Hope I'm wrong!

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
Please keep in mind the director of this film has also directed Incendies, Prisoners, Enemy, Sicario, and Arrival.  He has never made a bad or even 'okay' film yet, at least on a critical level. The cinematographer is also Roger Deakins, one of the best working today.  The personnel is top notch - people who know what they're doing.  Just because Ryan Gosling is frothed over by many women doesn't discredit him as a 'cheap' actor.  When directed right, he's a great actor, like in Drive and The Place Beyond The Pines.

I'm usually very skeptical of sequels of course, but that's because the intention is always purely to cash in.  But knowing the people working behind this film, I can put faith that they're passionate in making this film something special.

I'm personally very excited for this film, and I just hope I'm not getting my high expectations ahead of me.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: The story and the screenplay are by Hampton Fancher, the same man who took Philip K. Dick's novella and created out of it the screen play Blade Runner, and created its dark noir setting.  Fancher did not write Blade Runner's opening and annoying voice over, nor attempt to leave the viewer wondering if Decker was himself non-human. The original scripts, more than a dozen, remained true to Dick's original conclusion on whether an AI being could acquire a true consciousness.  Ridley argues for it, totally disregarding the original creator's point of view. As long as Fancher is on board I am quiet anxious to watch the sequel and see how faithful Ridley is, or is not, to Dick's argument on what is that element that makes man a man.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
This trailer is pretty disappointing. Blade Runner often feels like the only true cyberpunk movie, managing to realise the almost hallucinogenic descriptions of urban life in the future like in Neuromancer, while maintaining a fixation on the real message of the genre: technology will not save us. Innumerable benefits will be found with technological progression, but the ultimate mundanity of life will never cease. You've got a new bionic liver from a Japanese megacorporation but you've still got to pay the rent and feed your drug habit. There are also unsettling implications about the diminishing 'value' of a living person in a world of overwhelming scale and technological sophistication. All of this, conveyed in the style of a pulpy detective noir story. It's a masterpiece and it left you thinking for years after it finished.

This looks really goddamn stupid and flashy.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
Dialogue seems a bit hammy with too much exposition, preferred the more understated dialogue of the directors cut (not including the Harrison Ford monologues), and I hope lines delivered in the style of, "I always told you, you're special" aren't  previews to the rest of the dialogue (not that it's terrible, just mediocre Hollywood by the numbers stuff).

Visuals and sound look good, but there's been some definite dumbing down, there's now a more obvious villain, and a hamfisted android apartheid plot (echoes of the Ghost in the Shell plot turned into Robocop for the Hollywood remake), if you set your expectations to something around the Ghost in the Shell level or slightly better and are happy with that, you'll likely have a good time.

Hollywood making a great sequel or adaptation is an increasingly rare phenomenon, probably due to high levels of creative bankruptcy in the industry (and that lack of creativity is the reason they seem to keep trying to mine the past).

Hope I'm proved wrong.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: Although at first excited that one of my favorite movies  is getting a sequel, I'm a bit disappointed after watching this. It seems that today we are basically sold by super-hyped trailers to go and buy tickets. The majority of Hollywood movies seem to lack some deeper meaning, some message. Everything is just plain and visually beautiful.  The original Blade Runner was not only revolutionary for its visuals at the time, but more important, it was a philosophical movie. It was a movie that asked some existential questions.  And, the ending of the original was great because it left us with all these unanswered questions that every individual may direct and answer in its own way.  It left the possibility of discussion. Having the questions answered in the sequel leave us with nothing, it simplifies the whole concept of the primal idea of the Blade Runner story and universe. The other thing that doesn‚Äôt work for me, is casting big Hollywood names in a movie that is under so much pressure to bring something new. Casting Gosling was wrong, it just seems like this is not only a sequel to Blade Runner, but also to Drive and Only God Forgives. I think that they should have brought an unknown name to play the main character.

Comment:
Well... i don't know what to make of this. I really don't.   Arrival was... "interesting".  But honestly one of the most boring movies i've ever seen (compared to _Arrival_ ,  _Stalker_ was a truly interesting journey of some sort).
Now, the same director will bring us _Blade Runner 2049_ .   But okay, let's be fair here and just focus on the trailer. I'm missing the certain... "something" that Blade Runner had.  The constant rain, the depressive atmosphere, the (pseudo)philosophical talks... A Trailer is a alway like walking on a razors edge. One have to show some action and some calm, quiet moments, but of course not too much from the final film.  That goes especially for Blade Runner.

Time will tell. As for know, i'm going to wait in anticipation.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
This looks like a vanity project for all involved. 
Ryan "Pretty Boy" Gosling flexing his Drive clout by playing up the silent and tormented protagonist role. Every frame with him in it looks eye-roll inducing and also indicative of Denis Villieneve shameful attempt to cement his status in the imdb top 250.

Harrison Ford is there too, desperate to cling on to the virtues of his youth, despite destroying each of his iconic roles in the process. I'm sure old man Decard in a Hanes t-shirt throwing mediocre punches was oh so integral to this story. Reminds me of his role in Return of the Jedi where he spends the majority of the time trying to hack into a door, essentially playing no real part of the ongoing story. Even Ford himself admitted he should've been killed off long before in Empire. Why is Hollywood so intent on keeping Harrison around? Do we really want to see a 90 year old Indiana Jones come 2020? Give him new roles. 

Denis is a mediocre filmmaker coasting on his unabashed pandering to pseuds by employing cinematographers like Roger Deakins and cultivating his visual style to something that can be chalked up as "the thinking man's Zack Snyder." I'm sure Warner Bros. is even aware of this seeing as they're sculpting him to be their new go-to director.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment: This looks like it could be shite. The lines sound cheesy, like they are all trying to exude the importance of what they're saying. If they really are a part of this world then they're not going to be philosophizing about every little thing. AI robots have been around for decades so what's with all the grandiose talk. The cinematography looks technically excellent but there isn't a lot of grime or claustrophobia, or a distinct/coherent look to the film. The first film was very film-noir, cramped and dirty whereas in this I see a lot of different color palettes and styles, all very clean. In that sense it could be Total Recall or any other sci fi sequel. It's been through some dramatic color correction and that's too obvious. I'm not crazy about the casting choices. Nor am I crazy about Harrison Ford reappearing. He was what he was in the 80s and he doesn't have that charisma anymore, so it seems like he's there as a piece of nostalgia, handing off the mantle to Ryan Gosling. This type of thing worked ok in The Force Awakens, and it failed miserably in Kingdom of the Crystal Skull, but I've seen it twice already and I know I'm not interested in seeing it again. The little I've seen of Leto makes him look like a clich√© god figure, with none of the mystery or uniqueness of Tyrell in the first movie. As for the music I'm worried that jazzing up Vangelis' main theme with modern tropes is like putting big fake tits on an Audrey Hepburn lookalike and calling her Audrey Hepburn 2.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
The original is my favorite movie and I was very excited about this one after watching the first Trailer. Denis Villeneuve is an awesome director, but I don't know, after watching this one, there's something off about it. One of the best things about Blade Runner is it's pace, the movie is so slow and yet so powerful I don't even know how it works to be honest, 2049 seems too big, too fast, and I get it. It's obvious they would try to make it into a sci-fi action blockbuster, the movie is too expensive to be slow and contemplative, but I thought they would go in that direction when they announced the director, since that's what he does with his films, but with much smaller budgets. I was naive, and although it looks cool, I'm extremely sad and disappointed.
The dialogue is also too obvious, too expositive for my taste, it reminds me of Jonathan and Cristopher Nolan stuff, which is pretty bad since I find their movies quite shallow, which is the opposite of how I view Blade Runner.

Title: BLADE RUNNER 2049 - Official Trailer
Comment:
This preview looks awesome, but it had me worried at first. The original film was not really an action film. It was unique: a philosophical sci-fi noir film, more theater and tone than blockbuster. This trailer is a bit flashy, most likely the doing of marketing and editing. We‚Äôve probably already seen most of the gunshots and explosions in this film. 

Part of the beauty of the original, in all of its versions, was its ambiguity.  Was Deckard a replicant? What happened to him and Rachel? Based off of the trailer it appears the audience will get some answers. This could be a bad thing‚Äîor a good thing, but chances are slim. If anyone can do it, Denis is the guy. More likely is that he will retain most of the original‚Äôs ambiguity. I hope he does not answer too many questions‚Äîadmittedly I don‚Äôt think he will: he is a delightfully talented filmmaker whom I have faith in. But my faith is swayed when dealing with a story‚Äîa legacy‚Äîof this size.  But that is the nature of sequels.  I‚Äôm very excited to see this film. *let the hype train commence*

Comment: Bladerunner has been in my top 10 movies since I was a kid.  Villeneuve is top notch so it feels like we are in safe hands especially as Ridley has been off the boil for years. My only concern is that some of the design and replicants (costumes, hair) look too 'safe' compared to the original. Remember Rachel's hair and makeup? everything had this future noir - Jean Paul Gaultier feel about it... A heavily stylised future where as this feels like it wants to be more grounded and realistic.  Not necessarily bad, just more obvious. There was something quite organic and mystical about the craft flying over the skyline, the rain and the cosmopolitan streets filled with grime and neon.
